{{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = Sheikh Kamal International Cricket Stadium | native_name = শেখ কামাল আন্তর্জাতিক স্টেডিয়াম | nickname = Cox's Bazar Stadium | image = | caption = SKICS satellite view | country = Bangladesh | location = [[Cox's Bazar]], [[Chittagong Division]], Bangladesh | establishment = 2014 | seating_capacity = 7,800 (current) 100,000 (Expected)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cp.bangladeshinfo.com/headline/pm-to-open-sheikh-kamal-intl-stadium-today/|title=PM to open Sheikh Kamal Int’l Stadium today|publisher=bangladeshinfo.com|date=23 February 2014|accessdate=27 April 2015}}</ref> | owner = [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] | operator = [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] | tenants = | end1 = N/A | end2 = N/A | international = true | firstodidate = | firstodiyear = | firstodihome = | firstodiaway = | lastodidate = | lastodiyear = | lastodihome = | lastodiaway = | firsttestdate = | firsttestyear = | firsttesthome = | firsttestaway = | lasttestdate = | lasttestyear = | lasttesthome = | lasttestaway = | date = 05th May | year = 2015 | source = https://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/ground/689859.html, Sheikh Kamal International Cricket Stadium, Cricinfo }}
'''Sheikh Kamal International Stadium''' ({{lang-bn|শেখ কামাল আন্তর্জাতিক স্টেডিয়াম}}), also known as '''Cox's Bazar Cricket Stadium''' ({{lang-bn|কক্সবাজার ক্রিকেট স্টেডিয়াম}}), is a newly developed [[cricket]] stadium in the tourist town of [[Cox's Bazar]], [[Bangladesh]].
It was built on leased land from [[Cox's Bazar Golf Course]]. The stadium was a shortlisted venue for the [[2014 ICC World Twenty20]], however it did not host any matches due to the construction of the ground not finishing in time for the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2014/content/story/683115.html|title=Sylhet wins, Cox's Bazaar misses out|date=27 October 2013|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=27 October 2013}}</ref>
The first match played at the stadium was a [[Women's One Day International]] match between [[Bangladesh national women's cricket team|Bangladesh]] and [[Pakistan national women's cricket team|Pakistan]] on 5 March 2014. It also hosted 2 matches of [[Youth's One Day International]] between [[Bangladesh national under-19 cricket team| Bangladesh]] and [[South Africa national Under-19 cricket team| South Africa]]. Those 2 matches won by one each. <ref>{{cite web|title=Women beat Pakistan|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/sports/women-beat-pakistan-14147|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref> The venue has hosted 17 group matches of [[2016 ICC Under-19 Cricket World Cup]] (8 matches on academy ground). It also hosted (October 2017) 4 One-day matches between [[Bangladesh national cricket team| Bangladesh]] A and [[Ireland national cricket team| Ireland]] A, while one match being washed out.
