{{Refimprove|date=July 2015}} The '''Texas–U.S.S.R. Musicians' Exchange''' was a 1987 cultural exchange tour of the [[Soviet Union]] featuring a group of musicians from [[Texas]]. Among the musicians who performed on the tour were [[Butch Hancock]], Tomas Ramirez, [[Bobby Bridger]], Elouise Burrell, [[Bobby Mack]], Mike Shea, Deborah Giles, Bruce Truitt, Tom Ash, Steve Zirkel, Ron Rogers, Natasha Geddie, Jean Marie Houston, Bobby Williams, Ralph Taylor and Steve Parkess, who originally conceived of the project. The group performed and interacted with local musicians, artists and music fans in [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]], [[Moscow]] and [[Kiev]], and after leaving the Soviet Union the group opened for [[Chris Isaak]] at a concert in [[Helsinki, Finland]]. A limited-edition [[silk-screen]] print was created by [[graphic artist]] [[Nels Jacobson|Nels “Jagmo” Jacobson]] to publicize and commemorate the tour.
==References== *“Local artists to act as ambassadors of good music” by Michael Point from the ''Austin-American Statesman'' (September 24, 1987) {{ISSN|0199-8560}} *“Ten Days that Shook My World: Part I Leningrad: City that Peter the Great Built” by Tom Chamberlain from ''Current: San Antonio’s Newsweekly'' (November 12–18, 1987) *“Ten Days that Shook My World: Part II Kiev: On John Lennon’s Birthday” by Tom Chamberlain from ''Current: San Antonio’s Newsweekly'' (November 19–25, 1987) *“Ten Days that Shook My World: The Night Train to Moscow” by Tom Chamberlain from ''Current: San Antonio’s Newsweekly'' (December 3–9, 1987) {{Portal|1980s}}
